(44, 11, 1, 19, 22, 27, 27, 'the Gentiles had also received', 'Connection of Gentiles and Worship', 'This connection highlights the inclusion of Gentiles in the worship of God. Both passages emphasize that all nations will turn to the Lord and worship Him.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 1, 39, 1, 11, 11, 'Gentiles had also received the word of God', 'Gentiles Receiving God''s Word', 'This connection highlights the inclusion of Gentiles in God''s plan. Both passages emphasize that God''s name shall be great among the Gentiles, indicating a shared theme of divine outreach to non-Israelites.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 1, 23, 32, 15, 15, 'received the word of God', 'Spirit and Fruitfulness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of the spirit''s transformative power in both passages. Acts 11:1 speaks of the Gentiles receiving the word of God, while Isaiah 32:15 mentions the spirit being poured out, leading to fruitful outcomes.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 1, 45, 15, 7, 12, 'the Gentiles had also received the word of God', 'Gentiles Receiving God''s Word', 'This connection highlights the inclusion of Gentiles in God''s plan. Acts 11:1 notes that Gentiles received the word of God, while Romans 15:7-12 emphasizes that Gentiles glorify God for His mercy.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 1, 23, 49, 6, 6, 'Gentiles had also received the word of God', 'Connection of Gentiles and Salvation', 'This connection highlights the inclusion of Gentiles in God''s plan for salvation. Both passages emphasize the significance of the Gentiles receiving the word of God and being a light for them.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 1, 38, 8, 20, 23, 'Gentiles had also received the word of God', 'Gentiles Seeking the Lord', 'This connection highlights the theme of Gentiles receiving the word of God and seeking the Lord. Both passages emphasize the inclusion of nations and peoples in worship and prayer before God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 1, 44, 14, 27, 27, 'Gentiles had also received the word of God', 'Gentiles Receiving the Word', 'Both passages emphasize the inclusion of Gentiles in the faith. Acts 11:1 mentions the Gentiles receiving the word of God, while Acts 14:27 highlights how God opened the door of faith unto the Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 2, 44, 10, 45, 45, 'they that were of the circumcision', 'Astonishment of the Circumcision', 'Both passages emphasize the reaction of those ''of the circumcision'' to the inclusion of Gentiles in the faith. The astonishment in Acts 10:45 sets the stage for the contention mentioned in Acts 11:2, highlighting a significant moment of conflict within the early church.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 2, 44, 10, 9, 9, NULL, 'Peter''s Journey to Prayer', 'This connection highlights Peter''s actions as he transitions from prayer to facing opposition. Both passages emphasize Peter''s role in significant events that shape the early church.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 2, 44, 15, 1, 1, 'they that were of the circumcision', 'Circumcision and Salvation Debate', 'This connection highlights the contention regarding circumcision as a requirement for salvation. Both passages emphasize the conflict between those advocating for circumcision and the early Christian community''s understanding of salvation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 2, 44, 21, 20, 23, 'they that were of the circumcision contended with him', 'Controversy Over Jewish Customs', 'This connection highlights the ongoing contention regarding Jewish customs and the law. Both passages emphasize the conflict between Jewish believers and the teachings of Peter and Paul about circumcision and adherence to the law.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 2, 48, 2, 12, 14, 'they that were of the circumcision', 'Peter''s Withdrawal from Gentiles', 'This connection highlights Peter''s actions regarding the Gentiles, as seen in both passages. In Acts, Peter faces contention from those of the circumcision, while in Galatians, he withdraws from eating with Gentiles due to fear of them.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 3, 44, 10, 28, 28, 'men uncircumcised, and didst eat with them', 'Connection of Jewish Law and Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize the issue of Jews interacting with Gentiles. Acts 11:3 references eating with uncircumcised men, while Acts 10:28 discusses the unlawfulness of such associations, highlighting a significant shift in understanding regarding purity laws.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 3, 48, 2, 12, 12, 'didst eat with them', 'Eating with Gentiles', 'Both passages emphasize the act of eating with Gentiles, highlighting the tension between Jewish and Gentile believers. The SOURCE verse points to the criticism of Peter for associating with uncircumcised men, while the TARGET passage describes Peter''s withdrawal from eating with Gentiles due to fear of those from the circumcision party.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 3, 42, 15, 2, 2, 'didst eat with them', 'Eating with Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize the act of eating with those considered unclean or sinful. In Acts, Peter is criticized for eating with uncircumcised men, while in Luke, Jesus is criticized for receiving sinners and eating with them.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 3, 44, 10, 48, 48, 'men uncircumcised', 'Baptism and Acceptance of Gentiles', 'This connection highlights the acceptance of Gentiles in the early church. In Acts 11:3, the concern about eating with uncircumcised men relates to the baptism of those Gentiles in Acts 10:48.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 3, 46, 5, 11, 11, 'didst eat with them', 'Eating with Uncircumcised Men', 'This connection highlights the theme of association with those considered unclean or sinful. Both passages emphasize the implications of eating with individuals who do not adhere to certain moral or religious standards.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 3, 63, 1, 10, 10, NULL, 'Caution Against Unacceptable Associations', 'This connection highlights the concern over associating with those who do not adhere to proper doctrine. Both passages emphasize the importance of maintaining purity in fellowship and teaching.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 4, 42, 1, 3, 3, NULL, 'Orderly Presentation of Events', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of presenting information in a systematic manner. Peter ''expounded it by order'' in Acts, while Luke states he aims to write ''in order'' for Theophilus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 4, 6, 22, 21, 31, NULL, 'Witness and Rehearsal of Events', 'This connection highlights the theme of recounting significant events for the sake of future generations. Both passages emphasize the importance of clear communication and understanding among the people of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 4, 20, 15, 1, 1, NULL, 'Communication and Conflict Resolution', 'This connection highlights the importance of how words can influence reactions. Peter''s careful explanation in Acts reflects the idea that a soft answer can mitigate conflict, as noted in Proverbs.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 4, 44, 14, 27, 27, NULL, 'Rehearsing God''s Works', 'This connection highlights the act of rehearsing events related to God''s work among the Gentiles. Both passages emphasize the importance of recounting what God has done, showcasing the growth of the early church.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 44, 10, 9, 32, 'a certain vessel descend, as it had been a great sheet, let down from heaven by four corners', 'Vision of the Vessel', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s vision of a vessel descending from heaven, which signifies a divine message regarding clean and unclean animals. This vision serves as a pivotal moment leading to Peter''s encounter with Cornelius, illustrating the breaking of Jewish dietary laws and the inclusion of Gentiles.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 24, 1, 11, 14, NULL, 'Divine Communication in Visions', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine communication through visions. Both passages depict God revealing significant messages to His servants, with Peter in a trance and Jeremiah receiving visions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 26, 2, 9, 9, 'a certain vessel descend', 'Divine Communication in Visions', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine communication through visions. Both passages describe a significant revelation involving a vessel or roll sent from heaven, indicating God''s message to the recipient.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 30, 7, 4, 7, NULL, 'Divine Visions and Revelations', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine visions, as both passages describe God revealing significant messages to the prophets. In Acts, Peter experiences a vision in a trance, while Amos receives a vision from the Lord regarding judgment.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 30, 8, 2, 2, NULL, 'Divine Revelation and Judgment', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine revelation through visions, as seen in both passages. In Acts, Peter receives a vision that signifies a new understanding, while in Amos, the vision of summer fruit symbolizes impending judgment on Israel.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 44, 9, 10, 10, NULL, 'Visions in Prayer', 'Both passages emphasize the experience of receiving a vision while in prayer. This connection highlights the significance of divine communication through visions in moments of spiritual focus.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 5, 47, 12, 1, 3, NULL, 'Visions and Revelations Connection', 'Both passages emphasize experiences of visions and revelations from God. Acts describes a vision received during prayer, while 2 Corinthians discusses a man who experienced a profound revelation, highlighting the theme of divine communication.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 6, 42, 4, 20, 20, 'fastened mine eyes', 'Focus on the Eyes', 'This connection highlights the theme of attention and observation. In both passages, the act of fastening one''s eyes signifies a moment of significant focus and contemplation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 6, 44, 3, 4, 4, 'fastened mine eyes', 'Connection of Focused Attention', 'Both passages emphasize the act of ''fastening'' one''s eyes, indicating a deliberate focus on what is before them. This connection highlights the importance of attention in both contexts.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 8, 45, 14, 14, 14, 'nothing common or unclean', 'Clean and Unclean Concepts', 'Both passages emphasize the idea of what is considered clean or unclean. Acts 11:8 reflects Peter''s struggle with dietary laws, while Romans 14:14 asserts that nothing is unclean of itself, highlighting a shift in understanding regarding purity.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 8, 28, 9, 3, 3, 'nothing common or unclean', 'Connection of Clean and Unclean', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of unclean things. In Acts, Peter refuses to eat anything unclean, while Hosea describes Ephraim eating unclean things in Assyria.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 8, 46, 7, 14, 14, 'nothing common or unclean', 'Holiness and Cleansing Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of what is considered clean and unclean. In Acts 11:8, Peter refers to things that are unclean, while 1 Corinthians 7:14 discusses the sanctification of the unbelieving spouse and children, indicating a shift in their status from unclean to holy.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 8, 3, 10, 10, 10, 'nothing common or unclean hath at any time entered into my mouth', 'Clean and Unclean Distinction', 'Both passages emphasize the distinction between clean and unclean. Acts 11:8 reflects Peter''s adherence to dietary laws outlined in Leviticus 10:10, which instructs the faithful to differentiate between holy and unholy.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 8, 3, 11, 47, 47, 'nothing common or unclean', 'Clean and Unclean Distinction', 'This connection highlights the theme of distinguishing between clean and unclean. Acts 11:8 reflects Peter''s adherence to dietary laws, while Leviticus 11:47 establishes the criteria for these distinctions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 8, 15, 9, 11, 12, 'nothing common or unclean hath at any time entered into my mouth', 'Connection of Uncleanness Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of uncleanness. In Acts, Peter refers to what is unclean, while Ezra describes the land as filled with uncleanness due to the people''s abominations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 8, 41, 7, 2, 2, 'nothing common or unclean', 'Clean and Unclean Foods', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of cleanliness in relation to food. Acts 11:8 reflects Peter''s objection to eating unclean things, while Mark 7:2 discusses the criticism of disciples for eating with unwashen hands, highlighting the Jewish purity laws.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 9, 44, 15, 9, 9, NULL, 'Purification and Acceptance', 'This connection highlights the theme of purification and acceptance of all people. Both passages emphasize that God does not differentiate between groups, as seen in the cleansing and purifying of hearts.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 9, 58, 9, 13, 14, 'What God hath cleansed, that call not thou common', 'Cleansing and Purification Themes', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine cleansing in both passages. Acts 11:9 emphasizes what God has cleansed, while Hebrews 9:13-14 discusses the purifying power of Christ''s blood.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 9, 44, 10, 15, 15, 'What God hath cleansed, that call not thou common', 'Connection of Divine Cleansing', 'Both passages emphasize the phrase, ''What God hath cleansed, that call not thou common,'' highlighting a divine declaration about purity. This repetition underscores the importance of God''s authority in defining what is clean.', 'quotation', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 9, 44, 10, 28, 28, 'that call not thou common', 'God''s Cleansing of People', 'Both passages emphasize that God has declared certain individuals as clean, challenging Jewish customs regarding purity. This connection highlights the shift in understanding who is acceptable in God''s eyes.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 9, 44, 10, 34, 35, 'What God hath cleansed, that call not thou common', 'God''s Acceptance of All', 'This connection highlights the theme of God''s acceptance of individuals regardless of their background. Both passages emphasize that what God has cleansed should not be considered common, indicating inclusivity in God''s acceptance.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 9, 54, 4, 5, 5, 'What God hath cleansed', 'Sanctification and Cleansing', 'This connection highlights the theme of sanctification in both passages. Acts 11:9 speaks of what God has cleansed, while 1 Timothy 4:5 emphasizes that it is sanctified by the word of God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 10, 4, 24, 10, 10, 'three times', 'Three Times of Blessing and Vision', 'This connection highlights the repetition of ''three times'' in both passages, emphasizing significant moments of divine intervention. In Acts, the vision is repeated three times, while in Numbers, Balaam blesses three times instead of cursing.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 10, 43, 13, 38, 38, 'three times', 'Denial and Repetition Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of repetition in both passages. In Acts, the phrase ''three times'' indicates a significant repetition, while in John, Peter''s denial occurs ''thrice,'' emphasizing the importance of these repeated actions.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 10, 43, 21, 17, 17, 'this was done three times', 'Connection of Three Times', 'This connection highlights the repetition of ''three times'' in both passages, emphasizing significant moments in Peter''s experience. In Acts, the vision occurs three times, while in John, Jesus asks Peter three times about his love, indicating a theme of restoration and affirmation.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 10, 47, 12, 8, 8, NULL, 'Repeated Appeals to God', 'This connection highlights the theme of repetition in seeking divine intervention. Both passages emphasize the act of calling upon God three times for a response or change.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 11, 2, 4, 14, 14, NULL, 'Divine Guidance and Meeting', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine guidance in both passages. In Acts, the arrival of the three men is a direct intervention from God, similar to how God directs Moses to meet Aaron, who is already on his way.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 11, 2, 4, 27, 27, NULL, 'Divine Guidance and Meeting', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine guidance leading to significant meetings. In both passages, God directs individuals to encounter others at pivotal moments.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 11, 44, 9, 10, 12, NULL, 'Divine Guidance in Visions', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine guidance through visions. Both passages describe individuals receiving specific instructions from the Lord, emphasizing the importance of obedience to God''s call.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 11, 44, 10, 17, 18, 'three men already come unto the house', 'Divine Guidance in Peter''s Journey', 'Both passages emphasize the arrival of men sent to Peter, highlighting the divine orchestration of events. The mention of ''three men'' in Acts 11:11 connects directly to the ''men which were sent from Cornelius'' in Acts 10:17-18, illustrating the unfolding of God''s plan.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 12, 44, 8, 29, 29, 'the spirit bade me go', 'Guidance by the Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the directive of the Spirit in guiding individuals to specific actions. In Acts 11:12, the Spirit instructs Peter to go without doubt, while in Acts 8:29, the Spirit directs Philip to approach the chariot.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 12, 45, 3, 22, 22, 'nothing doubting', 'Faith and Acceptance', 'This connection highlights the theme of acceptance and belief. In Acts, the spirit guides Peter to accept Gentiles, while Romans emphasizes faith in Jesus Christ for all believers, indicating no distinction.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 12, 44, 10, 23, 23, 'these six brethren accompanied me', 'Peter''s Journey with Brethren', 'Both passages emphasize Peter''s decision to travel with certain brethren. In Acts 11:12, Peter mentions that ''these six brethren accompanied me,'' which directly connects to Acts 10:23 where he is described as being accompanied by ''certain brethren from Joppa.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 12, 53, 2, 2, 2, 'the spirit bade me go', 'Connection of Spiritual Guidance', 'This connection highlights the theme of being guided by the spirit. In Acts, the spirit directs action without doubt, while in 2 Thessalonians, there is a caution against being troubled by misleading spiritual messages.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 12, 40, 1, 20, 20, 'nothing doubting', 'Divine Guidance in Dreams', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine guidance through the Holy Spirit and angels. Both passages emphasize the importance of following divine instruction without doubt.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 12, 43, 16, 13, 13, 'the spirit bade me go', 'Guidance of the Spirit', 'This connection highlights the role of the Spirit in guiding believers. In Acts, the Spirit directs Peter to go without doubt, while in John, the Spirit of truth is promised to guide into all truth.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 12, 66, 22, 17, 17, 'the spirit bade me go', 'Invitation by the Spirit', 'This connection highlights the role of the Spirit in inviting individuals to respond. In Acts, the Spirit guides Peter to go without doubt, while in Revelation, the Spirit invites all to come and take the water of life.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 13, 44, 10, 30, 32, 'Send men to Joppa, and call for Simon', 'Divine Instruction to Cornelius', 'Both passages emphasize the instruction given to Cornelius to send for Peter in Joppa. The angel''s message in Acts 10:30-32 directly leads to the account in Acts 11:13, where this event is recounted.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 13, 44, 9, 43, 43, 'Simon, whose surname is Peter', 'Connection through Peter in Joppa', 'Both passages emphasize Simon Peter''s presence in Joppa. The mention of Peter in Acts 11:13 connects directly to his stay with Simon the tanner in Acts 9:43.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 13, 44, 10, 3, 6, 'Send men to Joppa, and call for Simon', 'Angel''s Message to Cornelius', 'Both passages emphasize the angel''s instruction to send men to Joppa for Peter. This connection highlights the divine guidance in Cornelius''s vision and Peter''s subsequent role in the narrative.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 13, 44, 12, 11, 11, 'an angel in his house', 'Angelic Intervention in Deliverance', 'This connection highlights the role of angels in guiding and delivering key figures in the early church. Both passages emphasize the presence of an angel and the subsequent actions taken by Peter in response to divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 13, 58, 1, 14, 14, 'an angel in his house', 'Angelic Messengers in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the role of angels as messengers in both passages. In Acts, an angel instructs Cornelius to seek Peter, while Hebrews describes angels as ministering spirits sent to aid believers.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 14, 44, 10, 22, 22, 'words, whereby thou and all thy house shall be saved', 'Connection of Salvation Messages', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of hearing words that lead to salvation. Acts 11:14 speaks of words that will save, while Acts 10:22 mentions hearing words from Peter, which are implied to be salvific.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 14, 44, 16, 15, 15, 'thy house', 'Salvation and Household Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of salvation extending to entire households. In Acts 11:14, the promise of salvation is directed to ''thy house,'' while Acts 16:15 shows a household being baptized, indicating a communal aspect of faith.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 14, 1, 17, 7, 7, 'all thy house shall be saved', 'Covenant and Salvation Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of salvation for households in both passages. Acts 11:14 speaks of salvation for ''all thy house,'' while Genesis 17:7 establishes a covenant with ''thy seed after thee,'' indicating a promise that extends to future generations.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 14, 43, 20, 31, 31, 'shall be saved', 'Salvation through belief', 'This connection highlights the theme of salvation through belief in Jesus. Acts 11:14 emphasizes the words that lead to salvation, while John 20:31 states that belief in Jesus brings life.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 14, 62, 5, 9, 13, 'words, whereby thou and all thy house shall be saved', 'Salvation and Eternal Life', 'This connection highlights the theme of salvation and eternal life found in both passages. Acts 11:14 speaks of words that lead to salvation, while 1 John 5:11-12 emphasizes that eternal life is found in the Son, linking belief in Christ to salvation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 14, 1, 18, 19, 19, 'thy house shall be saved', 'Salvation and Household Obedience', 'This connection highlights the importance of household faithfulness in both passages. Acts 11:14 speaks of salvation for a household, while Genesis 18:19 emphasizes Abraham''s role in guiding his household to keep the way of the Lord.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 14, 19, 19, 7, 11, 'words, whereby thou and all thy house shall be saved', 'Salvation and the Law', 'This connection highlights the theme of salvation through the words of the Lord. Both passages emphasize the importance of divine instruction in leading to spiritual transformation and ultimate salvation.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 15, 44, 19, 6, 6, NULL, 'Connection of Holy Spirit Events', 'Both passages emphasize the coming of the Holy Ghost upon believers, indicating a significant moment of empowerment. The phrase ''Holy Ghost came on them'' in Acts 19:6 parallels the experience described in Acts 11:15, highlighting a consistent theme of divine presence.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 15, 44, 2, 2, 12, 'Holy Ghost fell on them', 'Connection of the Holy Spirit', 'This connection highlights the falling of the Holy Ghost in both passages. Acts 11:15 refers to the Holy Ghost falling on the Gentiles, paralleling the initial outpouring of the Spirit in Acts 2:2-12.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 15, 44, 10, 34, 46, 'the Holy Ghost fell on them', 'Connection of the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the falling of the Holy Ghost on believers. In Acts 10:46, the Holy Ghost falls on Gentiles, while Acts 11:15 recalls this event as a significant moment for the early church.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 15, 44, 4, 31, 31, 'Holy Ghost fell on them', 'Connection of Holy Spirit Experiences', 'Both passages emphasize the filling of the Holy Ghost and the resulting boldness in speaking. Acts 11:15 refers to the Holy Ghost falling on individuals, similar to the filling described in Acts 4:31, highlighting a shared experience of empowerment by the Holy Spirit.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 16, 44, 1, 5, 5, 'ye shall be baptized with the Holy Ghost', 'Baptism with the Holy Ghost', 'Both passages emphasize the transition from John''s water baptism to the baptism with the Holy Ghost. This connection highlights the fulfillment of Jesus'' promise regarding the coming of the Holy Spirit.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 11, 16, 41, 1, 8, 8, 'baptized with the Holy Ghost', 'Baptism with the Holy Ghost', 'This connection highlights the theme of baptism, specifically the transition from water baptism to baptism with the Holy Ghost. Both passages emphasize the role of Jesus in this spiritual baptism.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
